00:00:47.690 --> 00:00:50.000
Well, the Anglo-Saxon
Kingdoms Exhibition

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:52.970
at the British Library
is the largest exhibition

00:00:52.970 --> 00:00:55.580
that there's ever been,
covering the whole period

00:00:55.580 --> 00:00:58.220
of the Anglo-Saxon
kingdoms, from the departure

00:00:58.220 --> 00:01:00.200
of the Romans right
up to the Norman

00:01:00.200 --> 00:01:03.320
conquest of 1066 and beyond.

00:01:03.320 --> 00:01:06.350
And it looks at the
history and the literature

00:01:06.350 --> 00:01:09.770
and the art of the
Anglo-Saxon kingdoms,

00:01:09.770 --> 00:01:13.430
examining the original
evidence that survives

00:01:13.430 --> 00:01:17.930
and bringing together some
of the greatest treasures.

00:01:17.930 --> 00:01:24.200
The impetus for the exhibition
was the acquisition in 2012

00:01:24.200 --> 00:01:29.660
of this little manuscript,
the "St. Cuthbert Gospel,"

00:01:29.660 --> 00:01:31.600
in my hand there.

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:35.010
And that little book
weighs only 162 grams,

00:01:35.010 --> 00:01:39.110
but it cost us 9 million pounds.

00:01:39.110 --> 00:01:42.900
And so we had-- it's the
earliest intact European book.

00:01:42.900 --> 00:01:44.750
And before its
acquisition, it was

00:01:44.750 --> 00:01:47.060
the most important
English medieval

00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:50.310
manuscript that was still
in private hands, I think.

00:01:50.310 --> 00:01:56.270
And we wanted to sort
of mark that acquisition

00:01:56.270 --> 00:02:01.430
by doing something
really on a large scale

00:02:01.430 --> 00:02:04.020
about the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms.

00:02:04.020 --> 00:02:07.370
The exhibition has
180 objects in it.

00:02:07.370 --> 00:02:09.530
80 of those come
from the library's

00:02:09.530 --> 00:02:14.000
own outstanding collection
of Anglo-Saxon manuscripts.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.910
You can see one of the most
famous here, the "Lindisfarne

00:02:16.910 --> 00:02:21.150
Gospels," made around 700.

00:02:21.150 --> 00:02:26.180
And so 80 of the objects
come from the library's

00:02:26.180 --> 00:02:26.940
own collection.

00:02:26.940 --> 00:02:29.240
And 100 are loans.

00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:33.690
The exhibition, I think, has
been popular for many reasons.

00:02:33.690 --> 00:02:38.120
But I think one of the
sources of its success

00:02:38.120 --> 00:02:42.350
is that it looks at the
beginnings and the foundation

00:02:42.350 --> 00:02:43.370
of so many things.

00:02:43.370 --> 00:02:46.135
It includes this manuscript,
which isn't actually

00:02:46.135 --> 00:02:48.260
an Anglo-Saxon manuscript,
dates from the beginning

00:02:48.260 --> 00:02:49.520
of the 12th century.

00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:51.460
And it's called the
"Textus Roffensis,"

00:02:51.460 --> 00:02:53.330
"Book of Rochester."

00:02:53.330 --> 00:02:58.100
And it is the
earliest manuscript

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:00.640
that we have of English law.

00:03:00.640 --> 00:03:02.660
So it contains the
laws of King Ethelberht

00:03:02.660 --> 00:03:06.140
of Kent compiled around 600.

00:03:06.140 --> 00:03:08.390
But it's also really
important because it's

00:03:08.390 --> 00:03:11.660
the earliest
extended text that we

00:03:11.660 --> 00:03:14.300
have that is written
in the English language

00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:16.235
and the beginnings of
the English language

00:03:16.235 --> 00:03:18.110
and English literature,
a theme running right

00:03:18.110 --> 00:03:20.040
through the exhibition.

00:03:20.040 --> 00:03:24.500
We also have in the exhibition
the first original charter

00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:27.860
that survives on the
sheet it was written on,

00:03:27.860 --> 00:03:32.510
on the left here, the
charter of [INAUDIBLE],, which

00:03:32.510 --> 00:03:36.710
dates from 679, granting
land in [INAUDIBLE]..

00:03:36.710 --> 00:03:39.470
And that is next to here
and in the exhibition

00:03:39.470 --> 00:03:43.130
next to the Letter
of World [? Hera, ?]

00:03:43.130 --> 00:03:47.450
which is the earliest
original letter that survives

00:03:47.450 --> 00:03:49.670
from Anglo-Saxon England.

00:03:49.670 --> 00:03:53.030
And this letter is
written in Latin.

00:03:53.030 --> 00:03:55.130
So we have earlier
letters, but this one

00:03:55.130 --> 00:03:57.630
survives on the original
piece of parchment

00:03:57.630 --> 00:03:59.240
it was first written on.

00:03:59.240 --> 00:04:03.540
And also in the exhibition,
we have this document,

00:04:03.540 --> 00:04:07.130
in which the scribe didn't waste
any of the parchment at all.

00:04:07.130 --> 00:04:09.470
This is the Fonthill Letter.

00:04:09.470 --> 00:04:11.270
And its claim to
fame is that it is

00:04:11.270 --> 00:04:14.150
the earliest letter
that survives written

00:04:14.150 --> 00:04:15.500
in the English language.

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:18.260
It's a letter to Edward
the Elder telling

00:04:18.260 --> 00:04:22.715
a tale of crime and punishment
about a disputed piece of land.

00:04:25.650 --> 00:04:28.880
There are many very beautiful
manuscripts in the exhibition.

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:34.070
And this manuscript contains
this very famous image

00:04:34.070 --> 00:04:36.490
of King Athelstan.

00:04:36.490 --> 00:04:39.230
And it is the first
portrait that we

00:04:39.230 --> 00:04:41.810
have of an English
king in a manuscript.

00:04:41.810 --> 00:04:44.370
There are portraits
of kings on old coins,

00:04:44.370 --> 00:04:46.490
but this is the first
one in a manuscript.

00:04:46.490 --> 00:04:49.760
And here, King
Athelstan is presenting

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:53.450
a copy of [? Thebes ?]
lives of Saint Cuthbert,

00:04:53.450 --> 00:04:56.270
the famous Northumbrian
Anglo-Saxon saint.

00:04:56.270 --> 00:04:58.580
And he's presenting
this manuscript

00:04:58.580 --> 00:05:02.330
to the community
of St. Cuthbert.

00:05:02.330 --> 00:05:05.250
So as I said, the
exhibition has at its heart

00:05:05.250 --> 00:05:08.960
80 manuscripts from the
library's own collections.

00:05:08.960 --> 00:05:12.740
But we also have
these 100 manuscripts

00:05:12.740 --> 00:05:14.600
and archaeological
objects on loan.

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:19.010
And we borrowed those
from 25 lenders.

00:05:19.010 --> 00:05:21.080
And some of those
manuscripts have never

00:05:21.080 --> 00:05:25.700
been seen in Britain before,
including this fantastic gospel

00:05:25.700 --> 00:05:29.670
book, the [INAUDIBLE]
Gospels on loan from Paris

00:05:29.670 --> 00:05:33.335
with this wonderful Lion of St.
Mark leaping across the page.

00:05:33.335 --> 00:05:35.990
This was made around 700.

00:05:35.990 --> 00:05:39.710
We have codex [INAUDIBLE],,
it's a giant Bible

00:05:39.710 --> 00:05:42.050
made at the beginning
of the eighth century

00:05:42.050 --> 00:05:45.500
and taken from
Northumbria to Italy.

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:47.540
It is one of the
greatest treasures

00:05:47.540 --> 00:05:49.310
of Anglo-Saxon England.

00:05:49.310 --> 00:05:52.370
And it has never
been back to England

00:05:52.370 --> 00:05:58.070
in 1300 years, until the day it
was delivered for installation

00:05:58.070 --> 00:06:01.950
in the exhibition.

00:06:01.950 --> 00:06:05.190
We have this manuscript, not
an Anglo-Saxon manuscript.

00:06:05.190 --> 00:06:08.180
This is the "Utrecht Psalter,"
"Book of the Psalms,"

00:06:08.180 --> 00:06:12.260
made in the first half of the
9th century on the continent

00:06:12.260 --> 00:06:15.470
and brought to
Canterbury, where it

00:06:15.470 --> 00:06:17.720
was used as a model
for other manuscripts,

00:06:17.720 --> 00:06:21.440
and it has these fantastic
cartoon-like strips,

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:26.810
decoration, illustration of
what is going on in the Psalms.

00:06:26.810 --> 00:06:31.460
This manuscript was in the
collection of Sir Robert

00:06:31.460 --> 00:06:33.650
Cotton, but he
lent it to a friend

00:06:33.650 --> 00:06:35.880
and it made its way
to the continent.

00:06:35.880 --> 00:06:39.950
And it's never been on
exhibition in Britain before,

00:06:39.950 --> 00:06:43.550
and neither has this manuscript,
the [? Bocelli ?] book.

00:06:43.550 --> 00:06:46.070
This is one of the four
principal manuscripts

00:06:46.070 --> 00:06:47.970
of Old English poetry.

00:06:47.970 --> 00:06:51.260
And we are displaying it
open at the poem known

00:06:51.260 --> 00:06:52.580
as the Dream of the Rood.

00:06:52.580 --> 00:06:55.160
So it's the dream
of the cross telling

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:59.180
the story of the crucifixion
from the cross' point of view.

00:06:59.180 --> 00:07:03.110
And it's been in Italy for
nearly 1,000 years, at least.

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:06.860
And the loan of
that manuscript has

00:07:06.860 --> 00:07:10.970
enabled us to display together
for the very first time

00:07:10.970 --> 00:07:15.560
the four principal manuscripts
of Old English poetry, which

00:07:15.560 --> 00:07:19.850
together contains 75% of
all the old English poetry

00:07:19.850 --> 00:07:21.215
that survives.

00:07:21.215 --> 00:07:25.740
And it's there, second on the
left, next to, on the left,

00:07:25.740 --> 00:07:27.600
the unique manuscript
of "Beowulf"

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:29.978
from our own collections.

00:07:29.978 --> 00:07:31.520
And if you've been
to the exhibition,

00:07:31.520 --> 00:07:34.790
you will have seen that there
is a replica of the Ruthwell

00:07:34.790 --> 00:07:38.720
Cross in the exhibition in
this language and literature

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:39.770
section.

00:07:39.770 --> 00:07:42.500
And the Ruthwell
Cross, on its sides,

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:47.510
has inscriptions
in runes, which are

00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:50.610
extracts from that poem,
The Dream of the Rood,

00:07:50.610 --> 00:07:52.070
so you see it--

00:07:52.070 --> 00:07:58.220
you see poetry on the parchment
pages but also on the stone.

00:07:58.220 --> 00:08:00.740
And right at the end
of the exhibition,

00:08:00.740 --> 00:08:04.760
we have "Domesday "Book,
the most famous book,

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:07.740
I think, in English history.

00:08:07.740 --> 00:08:11.080
And of course, this isn't an
Anglo-Saxon manuscript either.

00:08:11.080 --> 00:08:16.550
It was written up in 1086,
and it's on loan to us

00:08:16.550 --> 00:08:17.960
from the National Archives.

00:08:17.960 --> 00:08:24.770
And it's famous as a product of
Norman control and efficiency,

00:08:24.770 --> 00:08:28.580
but actually, "Domesday
Book" tells us so much

00:08:28.580 --> 00:08:33.980
that we can't see from any
other source about the landscape

00:08:33.980 --> 00:08:38.870
and the organization and the
wealth of late Anglo-Saxon

00:08:38.870 --> 00:08:39.710
England.

00:08:39.710 --> 00:08:43.549
So it's absolutely
fantastic, unique evidence

00:08:43.549 --> 00:08:46.290
for that period.

00:08:46.290 --> 00:08:49.790
So I'm going to hand over
now, after that very brief

00:08:49.790 --> 00:08:52.910
introduction, to Jo and Simon,
who are going to take us

00:08:52.910 --> 00:08:53.930
through the centuries.

00:08:53.930 --> 00:08:57.540
They're going to alternate,
looking at a manuscript

00:08:57.540 --> 00:09:01.490
and then a charter
in turn to take us

00:09:01.490 --> 00:09:05.360
into more depth about a few
of the highlight exhibits.

00:09:05.360 --> 00:09:07.472
Thanks.

00:09:07.472 --> 00:09:08.180
JOANNA STORY: OK.

00:09:08.180 --> 00:09:08.990
Thanks, Claire.

00:09:08.990 --> 00:09:09.950
Simon, you come here.

00:09:09.950 --> 00:09:10.460
Right.

00:09:10.460 --> 00:09:12.127
So I'm going to talk
about a manuscript,

00:09:12.127 --> 00:09:13.880
Simon's going to
talk about a charter,

00:09:13.880 --> 00:09:16.422
and the idea is that were going
to move through the centuries

00:09:16.422 --> 00:09:17.690
seamlessly, all right?

00:09:17.690 --> 00:09:20.720
And we've got about 3
and 1/2 minutes per item,

00:09:20.720 --> 00:09:22.220
so if you see me
